SSH (Secure Shell)
🎯 Objective

Learn what SSH is, why it is used, how it works, understand SSH key authentication, common SSH commands, and how SSH is used in Linux and AWS.

📖 What is SSH?

SSH (Secure Shell) is a network protocol used to securely connect to a remote computer over a network.

It encrypts all communication between the client and the server, making it safe to manage Linux servers remotely.

Default Port: 22

Why Do We Need SSH?

Imagine your Linux server is hosted on AWS in another city or country.

Without SSH:

You would need physical access to the server.
Remote administration would be impractical.

With SSH:

You can securely log in from anywhere.
Execute commands remotely.
Transfer files securely (using SCP or SFTP).
Manage servers without being physically present.
How SSH Works
+-----------------+        Internet        +-----------------+
| SSH Client      | --------------------> | SSH Server      |
| (Your Laptop)   |                       | (Linux Server)  |
+-----------------+                       +-----------------+
The client initiates a connection to the server on port 22.
The server proves its identity.
Authentication occurs (password or SSH key).
An encrypted session is established.
SSH Authentication Methods
1. Password Authentication
Username + Password
Easy to use
Less secure than keys
2. SSH Key Authentication (Recommended)

Uses two keys:

Private Key  → Stored securely on your computer
Public Key   → Stored on the remote server

Only someone with the matching private key can authenticate


SSH Key Pair
+------------------+
| Private Key      |
| id_rsa           |
+------------------+
        │
        │
        ▼
+------------------+
| Public Key       |
| id_rsa.pub       |
+------------------+




Common SSH Commands
Connect to a Remote Server
ssh username@server-ip

Example:

ssh ubuntu@192.168.1.100
Connect Using a Private Key
ssh -i mykey.pem ubuntu@server-ip

Example for AWS EC2:

ssh -i my-key.pem ubuntu@13.233.xxx.xxx
Generate an SSH Key Pair
ssh-keygen

Keys are typically stored in:

~/.ssh/
Copy Public Key to a Server
ssh-copy-id username@server-ip

Check the SSH Version
ssh -V


Linux Commands

List your SSH keys:

ls -la ~/.ssh

Display your public key:

cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub

(If your system uses newer defaults, the files may be id_ed25519 and id_ed25519.pub.)

Generate a new key pair:

ssh-keygen -t ed25519
AWS EC2 Example

When launching an EC2 instance:

Create or select a key pair.
Download the .pem file.
Set correct permissions:
chmod 400 my-key.pem
Connect to the instance:
ssh -i my-key.pem ubuntu@EC2-Public-IP



